<chapter xml:id="chapter-comp-inv" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Composite and inverse functions</title>

<section xml:id="section-comp-inv-comp">
<title>Composite functions</title>

<p>
The examples in <xref ref="section-chain-differential-version" /> all had a similar pattern to the initial approach:
we made a substitution for <m>u</m> based on recognizing an inner component and an outer component to the function.
For example,
for <me> q(t) = \sin^3(t) = {\bbrac{\sin(t)}}^3 </me>
from <xref ref="example-chain-power-of-sine" />,
the inner component is the sine function and the outer component is a power function.
For <me> q(t) = \sqrt{t^2 + 1} </me>
from <xref ref="example-chain-radical" />,
the inner component is a polynomial function and the outer component is the square root component.
It is just a matter of changing perspective on the function from a single input-output process to a <emph>chain</emph> of two (or more) input-output processes.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-chain-composite-input-output-schematic">
	<caption> Schematic of a function as a chained multi-step input-output process. </caption>
	<image width="66%">
		<description>Schematic of a function as a chained multi-step input-output process.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="chain.d/inner-outer.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<definition>
	<title>Composite of two functions</title>
	<p>
	Given functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>,
	the composite function <m>\comp{g}{f}</m> is the function defined by
	<me> (\comp{g}{f})(t) = g\bbrac{f(t)} </me>.
	If <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> are described in terms of formulas,
	a formula for <m>(\comp{g}{f})(t)</m> can be obtained by replacing every occurrence of <m>t</m> in the formula for <m>g(t)</m> with the entire formula for <m>f(t)</m>.
	</p>
</definition>

